@Andrew

Use the theme.  The full answer is INDICT, the final T being the large group of black squares.

Did you not notice that several other down answers needed the final T to complete the answer?

@Sharon

Yeah, thanks.  I realized that after I posted. 

Mea Culpa.

@Andrew
I feel like I say this a lot, but whatevs:

If you read more books, you will be better able to recognize words like INDIC. Be curious about the world. Learn more. It will make your crossword life so much easier.

@Steve L 

I don't know where those stats come from, but on checking my time (and doing the math) I finished in about 65(ish) percent of my Thursday average. 

It was actually pretty close to my Wednesday average (but only 50% of this week's Wednesday - which I struggled with).

@Wggwg
A famous maestro once heard some orchestra members grousing about having to plough through some old warhorse of a piece -- say, Beethoven's 5th. He reminded them, "Somewhere in tonight's audience is someone who has never heard this piece of music before. Play it to them."
Et sim. We grizzled veterans may know sll this but somewhere here is someone who hasn't faced this before.

@Grace G

So now the question is:  Should we be outraged either by the plagiarism of the theme by the setters or the editors' failure to catch the inadvertent callback or both or should we be grateful for a challenging Thursday, even if my subconscious was nagging me while solving that there was something familiar here?

I'm torn.

@Grace G

Well, not identical.  The clues and answers are different, so it's not an exact plagiarism.  But both puzzles have five large T's made out of black squares.  

So, very much the same theme, although the T's worked in both directions in the 2020 example Grace G so generously found for us.

@Mike
Sometimes I feel warm and cozy about replying, but today I'll just bag it.

PS.  If you need some Earl Grey, Rev. Spooner has some in a jar, dealing it out when asked.

@john ezra

Brilliant finale!!!  Just brilliant!!

Encore!!!!

@SBK in TO

DOWNTOAT resonated with me immediately.  I take it to mean “very precise” … exactly as clued.  I’ve not heard “done” to a T before.  But perhaps that’s a thing also.  I’m quite sure the DOWN expression is common. 

Mark

@SP

Regarding 1-A, I confused my "ventricles" with my ATRIA, and thought the answer was going to be "veins" or "venae".  When that supplied no helpful crossings, I put it aside for later.
It ended up being the last area of the (delightfully) tricky puzzle to fall for me.

@Weak

Not my journey tonight, but I do recognize it from other nights.

It's amazing how we forget about the black background in these puzzles, forget even to look at them.

@v

The clue was [Modern intensifying suffix].  No mention of body parts. Any scatalogical connection is on you. 

The word from which all variations derive is a reference to an unintelligent donkey. That makes more sense than an unintelligent tushie.

@Charles Peterson
I have pearls but I don't clutch them every time I am disappointed by the degradation of our shared language. I'd have long since strangled myself.
And the word in question may relate to donkeys or to your sit-me-down 😏.  But Dickens notwithstanding, it is not a word I am happy to see here.

@Heidi
Thank you for keeping that catch phrase afloat!  It shall live on forever!
Or at least another couple weeks.

@M
If you think you can construct a puzzle without needing to use any fill such as ADP or SSN, you are welcome to try. I'm sure it will be a masterpiece.

As for Naticks: there weren't any. None of the proper nouns in this puzzle are crossing each other. A Natick is when two proper nouns cross each other, and their shared letter can't be easily deduced.

@Xword Junkie

I'm with you.
But, since the theme was so easily inferred, it doesn't rise to PoY status, IMHO.

