Such was my solve today. On again, off again despite catching onto the T-theme early.

@Dale M

It’s a geographical indicator of a language group. 

Indic-actor?

@Sean
yeah, it's feminine so the Latin plural would have been AORTAE. 
An earlier poster entered AORTA, mentally placed the E in the black square next to 5, and then used it as the first letter of (E)VENT going down.  That must have been a mess to clean up!

@Bob T.
Is this like cilantro? If you've got a particular gene, the stuff tastes like soap to you. If you don't, it has a green herb-y taste. (I'm in the soapy crowd.)
But I've never heard this suggested for gin.

@Laura Stratton

Today’s puzzle was not a rebus in the way that I think you mean. It’s a rebus only in the sense that the final letter is represented by a picture (the black squares forming a T). If you entered two letters into a square, that would be wrong. For example, if you entered EVENT by putting N and T into a single square, you would end up with EVENTT once the rebus T was applied. That makes it an incorrect entry.

If I misunderstood your issue, I apologize.

@Laura Stratton

I still don’t understand what you’re saying, or maybe you’ve figured it out since you asked. There are no rebuses (multiple letters in the white squares). The final T’s are omitted because the large black T’s in the grid substitute for them. So the across answers above each black T all make sense, and the down answers above those T’s are filled in without their final T’s. 

Hope this helps!

